-a, --address <ip address>\tstring to send as your ip address\n
-b, --cache-file <file>\tfile to use for caching the ipaddress\n
-c, --config-file <file>\tconfiguration file, almost all arguments can be\n
\t\t\t\tgiven with: <name>[=<value>]\n\t\t\t\tto see a list of possible config commands\n
-d, --daemon\t\t\trun as a daemon periodicly updating if \n\t\t\t\tnecessary\n
-e, --execute <command>\tshell command to execute after a successful\n\t\t\t\tupdate\n
-f, --foreground\t\twhen running as a daemon run in the foreground\n
-m, --mx <mail exchange>\tstring to send as your mail exchange\n
-M, --max-interval <# of sec>\tmax time in between updates\n
-N, --notify-email <email>\taddress to send mail to if bad things happen\n
-p, --resolv-period <sec>\tperiod to check IP if it can't be resolved\n
-P, --period <# of sec>\tperiod to check IP in daemon \n\t\t\t\tmode (default: 1800 seconds)\n

-R, --run-as-user <user>	change to <user> for running, be ware
				that this can cause problems with handeling
				SIGHUP properly if that user can't read the
				config file. also it can't write it's pid file 
				to a root directory

-Q, --run-as-euser <user>	change to effective <user> for running, 
				this is NOT secure but it does solve the 
				problems with run-as-user and config files and 
				pid files.
-S, --service-type <server>\tthe type of service that you are using\n
-t, --timeout <sec.millisec>\tthe amount of time to wait on I/O\n
-T, --connection-type <num>\tnumber sent to TZO as your connection \n\t\t\t\ttype (default: 1)\n
-U, --url <url>\t\tstring to send as the url parameter\n
-u, --user <user[:passwd]>\tuser ID and password, if either is left blank \n\t\t\t\tthey will be prompted for\n
-w, --wildcard\t\tset your domain to have a wildcard alias\n
-1, --once\tin daemon mode, update once then exit\n
signals are only really used when in daemon mode.
